  "text": "In both genotypes, the saline-conditioned group exhibited no preference for either place. The mean conditioning scores were 4.8 Ϯ 41.3 sec for wild-type mice and Ϫ12.7 Ϯ 46.6 sec for dopamine D 3 knock-out mice. The dose-response curves for morphine-induced place preference in wild-type and dopamine D 3 receptor knock-out mice are shown in Figure 3 . In wild-type mice, morphine (1-5 mg/kg, s.c.) produced a dose-dependent place preference for drug-associated place (144.7 Ϯ 43.9 sec for 5 mg/kg morphine; F (1,24) ϭ 5.38; p Ͻ 0.05; vs saline group) (Fig.  3A) . In dopamine D 3 receptor knock-out mice, lower doses of morphine (0.1-0.56 mg/kg, s.c.) produced a significant and dose-dependent place preference for drug-associated place (146.8 Ϯ 35.2 sec for 0.56 mg/kg morphine; F (1,17) ϭ 6.50; p Ͻ 0.05; vs saline group) (Fig. 3A) . The dose relationship for the morphine-induced place preference in dopamine D 3 receptor knock-out mice was significantly shifted to the left by 7.25-fold ( p Ͻ 0.01 vs wild-type mice) (Fig. 3A) . In addition, the place preference induced by 0.56 mg/kg morphine in dopamine D 3 receptor knock-out mice was completely blocked by intracerebroventricular treatment with CTOP (100 pmol per mouse; 11.3 Ϯ 47.8 sec; F (1,16) ϭ 7.24; p Ͻ 0.05; vs saline-morphine group) (Fig. 3B) . Figure 4 shows the morphine-induced hyperlocomotion in wildtype and dopamine D 3 knock-out mice. We first found that the mutant mice exhibited an enhanced locomotion in the novel environment (during 4 hr habituation; data not shown). This result was consistent with the report by [CITATION_1] . After 4 hr habituation, saline treatment produced no differences in locomotion between wild-type and dopamine D 3 knock-out mice; the mean total activity counts for 180 min were 215.2 Ϯ 42.7 and 294.8 Ϯ 91.3 counts per 180 min, respectively (Fig. 4 B) . Morphine (5 mg/kg, s.c.) produced a significant increase in locomotion in both genotypes [wild-type mice (F (1,189) ϭ 13.3; p Ͻ 0.01 vs saline) and dopamine D 3 knock-out mice (F (1,210) ϭ 72.9; p Ͻ 0.001 vs saline)]. Under these conditions, the morphine-induced locomotor enhancing effect was significantly enhanced by a deletion of dopamine D 3 receptor gene (Fig. 4) .",
